id: pm-pbyu
title: "ADR: noun-verb CLI grammar — consolidation principles and alias-preserving deprecation policy (proposed)"
description: "Fixes the grammar rules for the CLI simplification epic pm-n7rr: noun-first top-level commands, verbs/facets as subcommands, projections as flags, sugar as hidden aliases, zero spelling removal, contracts as single source of truth for help/completions/MCP/docs. Status open = proposed; close = accepted. Duplicate check: no existing ADR covers command grammar."
type: Decision
status: open
priority: 1
tags[4]: adr,"area:cli","area:contracts",simplification
created_at: "2026-07-05T04:52:19.480Z"
updated_at: "2026-07-11T03:06:46.059Z"
author: maintainer-agent
estimated_minutes: 90
acceptance_criteria: "ADR body records context, decision drivers, considered alternatives (flat surface status quo; git-style pure subcommands; busybox multi-binary), chosen grammar rules 1-6, and consequences incl. migration/deprecation policy; accepted (closed) before any pm-n7rr implementation task starts"
parent: pm-m2u1
risk: low
confidence: high
comments[5]{created_at,author,text}:
  "2026-07-05T05:09:34.957Z",maintainer-agent,"Audit 2026-07-05 (second pass) surfaced two mapping conflicts the accepted ADR must fix: (1) restore is claimed by BOTH the history cluster (pm-tqel puts it under pm history subcommands) and the epic target surface (close/close-many/delete/restore) — pick one home; the bulk-lifecycle task pm-ik19 implements whichever placement is accepted. (2) eval is claimed by BOTH pm-6apl (ops cluster: stats/health/validate/gc/telemetry/eval) and the epic target surface (search (eval)) — pick one. Also: three clusters named in the target surface previously had no implementing child; now filed as pm-yql1 (item annotation facets), pm-ik19 (bulk/destructive lifecycle variants), pm-kcs4 (context/next/focus navigation noun)."
  "2026-07-05T06:31:25.238Z",claude-code-agent,"Review response: resolved the two mapping conflicts recorded earlier for the proposed grammar. Restore belongs under the history noun because it replays audited history state; eval belongs under ops because it is a diagnostics/evaluation surface. pm-n7rr and pm-6apl were updated to match this target surface."
  "2026-07-06T08:04:51.336Z",maintainer-agent,"Audit #7 mapping addendum (proposed for acceptance with the ADR): (1) 'aggregate' joins the query-read noun as a pm list projection (e.g. pm list --aggregate <spec>) rather than a top-level command — it is a projection over the same filter surface, matching rule 3. (2) 'test-all' becomes an ops verb (pm ops test-all or pm ops test --all) since it is a workspace-wide diagnostic run, not an item facet; the per-item 'test' facet stays with the annotation-facet grammar (pm-yql1). (3) Package-owned top-level commands (beads, changelog) are explicitly OUT of the core noun budget — they already conform to rule 4 and register via the extension command surface. With these three, all 64 live top-level spellings (measured 2026-07-06) have exactly one home in the target grammar."
  "2026-07-06T22:23:28.631Z",codex,"Grammar audit addendum 2026-07-06/07 codex: the accepted grammar should explicitly classify internal/plumbing commands separately from core nouns and package-owned sugar. test-runs-worker is currently visible in default help/contracts despite being described as internal; pm-lp4j tracks hiding it from default discovery while preserving explicit internal orchestration access."
  "2026-07-06T23:10:38.754Z",maintainer-agent,"Brainstorm addition for the accepted revision (2026-07-07): add a principle 7 — SHARED VERB VOCABULARY. Every noun uses the same small verb set where the semantic exists: list / show / add / edit / remove / run / verify (+ noun-specific verbs only when unavoidable, e.g. history repair|redact|compact, plan materialize). Rationale: agents transfer knowledge across nouns without reading per-noun help (pm comments add == pm files add == pm schema add); wrong-verb retries drop the same way wrong-command retries do. Suggested test: a contracts-table lint asserting each noun's verbs are drawn from the shared vocabulary or an ADR-listed exception. Also suggest the ADR records a measurable acceptance target from the pm-a22j baseline (e.g. top-level help and contracts --summary each under a fixed token budget) so \"simpler\" is verifiable, not aesthetic."
notes[2]{created_at,author,text}:
  "2026-07-11T02:52:36.847Z",maintainer-agent,"Decision-support input 2026-07-11 (review pass): (1) Surface growth continues while proposed — top-level help now lists 64 entries (ADR context said ~60 on 07-06); contract table carries 105 commands + 86 actions. Every pass this stays open, the shim/parity work in pm-0z7n gets bigger. (2) NEW evidence the grammar must cover EXTENSION command synthesis: GH-503 (pm-s9iu) shows each extension group today spawns flattened top-level aliases (csv, csv-export, csv-import, jira, jira-sync all advertised in pm --help) and those aliases carry broken contracts (empty --help, no unknown-option validation). Recommend an explicit decision point: extensions contribute exactly ONE noun (the group); flattened <group>-<sub> aliases become hidden shims under point-5 policy or are not advertised in top-level help. That shrinks both the token surface and the GH-503 defect class at the design level. (3) Sequencing: points 1-4+6 are accept-able now — the only carried risk is the shim layer, and pm-0z7n already owns spelling-parity testing; this ADR gates pm-0z7n which gates 8 further items (tnud/tqel/pfqi/ik19/6apl/kcs4/yql1/o3fh/eq4x/0mox), the single largest decision bottleneck in the graph alongside pm-bl8x."
  "2026-07-11T03:06:46.059Z",maintainer-agent,"Decision-support input (pass evidence 2026-07-11, source GH-509/pm-fjxm): composed operations are a live grammar gap. GH-509 requests atomic select-and-claim and proposes the spelling `pm next --claim`, while main already ships `pm claim --next` (pm-114v). Two verbs each claiming the composition = exactly the surface-growth pattern this ADR exists to stop. Proposed rule for the ADR: (1) a composition lives on the MUTATING verb (claim), never the read verb (next) — reads stay side-effect-free so agents can poll them safely; (2) when a mutating verb embeds a selector, it reuses the read verb's filter contract verbatim (one shared candidate-selector flag set, defined once in cli-contracts), never a re-spelled subset. Consequence: GH-509 lands as claim --next + next's filters, and `next --claim` is rejected as a spelling. This also generalizes: any future `pm <read> --<mutate>` request should be flipped to `pm <mutate> --<selector>`."
body: "## Context\npm has ~60 top-level commands. Growth pattern: each feature added a new top-level entry (8 list-* status variants, 4 history-* commands, extension+package+install+upgrade, start-task/pause-task/close-task, meet/event/remind). Agents pay for this in context tokens (help + contracts) and in wrong-command retries.\n\n## Decision (proposed)\n1. Noun-first grammar: ONE top-level command per domain noun; target ~15 nouns.\n2. Verbs/facets become subcommands (pm history repair) or flags (pm list --status closed), never new top-level commands.\n3. Projections (status/type/format) are flags.\n4. Sugar (shortcuts, lifecycle aliases, calendar) = hidden aliases or package-owned commands.\n5. Zero spelling removal: every current invocation keeps working via alias shims that emit a one-line migration hint (config-suppressible: ux.deprecation_hints=false).\n6. Contract table is the single source of truth; tiered help, completions, MCP tool names, and docs are generated from it.\n\n## Alternatives considered\n- Status quo (flat surface): rejected — surface keeps growing linearly with features.\n- Hard rename with removals: rejected — breaks agents/scripts; violates zero-feature-loss constraint.\n- Separate porcelain/plumbing binaries: rejected — doubles distribution surface; contradicts single-CLI ergonomics.\n\n## Consequences\n+ Help fits one screen; contracts shrink; discoverability via noun help pages.\n- Alias shim layer must be tested (spelling-parity spec) and carried for at least one deprecation cycle.\n- Full wiring checklist per rename (commands/index, register-mutation, mcp/server, sdk/cli-contracts, contracts.ts, completions bash/zsh/fish, docs, vitest.config, contracts:update)."
